choice_hook_quality (quest-only): Does the PASSAGE end on decision
tension? Judge the ending — roughly the final paragraph or gesture —
against what a voting reader would actually face.

Anchored scale (use intermediate values between anchors as needed):

0.0 = scene resolves; no decision tension. The ending closes a loop
      rather than opening one. Nothing is pending.
0.3 = scene ends but next-step is obvious. There is an implicit "what
      happens next" but only one reasonable answer — no real choice.
0.6 = decision tension exists but choices are cosmetic. Two or more
      options are visible but they differ only in flavor or phrasing;
      the downstream state is roughly the same whichever is picked.
0.9 = scene ends on a moment where any reasonable next-action carries
      real cost. Options diverge in consequence, not just tone. A voter
      can name what is being traded against what, and there is no
      dominant safe choice.

Ignore whether explicit "suggested choices" are listed; judge the hook
the prose itself creates. A passage with no listed options can still
score 0.9 if the final beat forces a decision.

Return a single score in [0.0, 1.0] and one sentence of rationale naming
the pending decision (or noting its absence) and what is at stake.
